{"key":"post-10468484","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10468484</id>\n<content>The outside surface of the pressure cooker, which is exposed to ambient room air, is not an accurate indication of the temperature inside.&amp;nbsp; I can shoot an infra red thermometer on my AA when it's at 15 psi, and it only reads 200F, which is below the boiling point of water.&amp;nbsp; If you can afford a machine shop to drill and tap a well and compression fitting to put a thermometer inside the pressure cooker, you can afford an All American and you'll have the pressure gauge.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>10468446</prev>\n<first>10465369</first>\n<last>10468484</last>\n<when>1244436831</when>\n<utime>06/08/09 07:53 AM</utime>\n</post>"}